    True or False?
    When clustering, we want to put two data objects that are similar into the same cluster.
    True
    True or False?
    Cluster analysis is considered supervised learning.
    False. Cluster analysis is by definition unsupervised learning.
    True or False? It is impossible to cluster objects in a data stream. We must have all the data objects that we need to cluster ready before clustering can be performed.
    False. Clustering algorithms can be adapted to perform clustering in a streaming fashion
    True or False? Clustering analysis has a wide range of applications in tasks such as data summarization, dynamic trend detection, multimedia analysis, and biological network analysis.
    True
    True or False? Clustering analysis is unsupervised learning since it does not require labeled training data.
    True
    True or False? Clustering analysis has a wide range of applications in tasks such as data summarization, dynamic trend detection, multimedia analysis, and biological network analysis.
    True
    True or False? It is impossible to cluster objects in a data stream. We must have all the data objects that we need to cluster ready before clustering can be performed.
    False. This is false because clustering algorithms can be adapted to perform clustering in a streaming fashion.
    True or False? When clustering, we want to put two dissimilar data objects into the same cluster.
    False. This is false because, as discussed in the lecture, the objective of clustering is having similar objects in the same cluster.
    True or False? K-means is an example of a distance-based clustering method.
    • True
    True or False? Dimensionality reduction helps make high-dimensional clustering more feasible and scalable.
    True
    True or False? Since cluster analysis is unsupervised learning, there’s no way to incorporate user preference or guidance into the clustering process.
    False
    True or False? There are no clustering algorithms that can handle time-series data since we always assume that the data points are temporally independent from each other.
    False
    True or False? Graphs, time-series data, text, and multimedia data are all examples of data types on which cluster analysis can be performed.
    True
    True or False? When dealing with high-dimensional data, we sometimes consider only a subset of the dimensions when performing cluster analysis.
    True
    True or False? Agglomerative clustering is an example of a distance-based clustering method.
    True
    True or False? We can only visualize the clustering results when the data is two-dimensional.
    False. This is false because we can also easily visualize clusters in 3D. HD-eye is an example of software used for visualizing higher dimensional clusters.
    Clustering or Supervised Learning? Given the historical prices of a group of stocks, predict whether the price of a specific stock will rise or fall in the following week.
    Supervised Learning. The task is more suitable to using supervised learning because there is available training data that allows us to learn classifiers for prediction.
    Clustering or Supervised Learning? Find user communities in online social networks such as Facebook and Twitter
    Clustering
    Clustering or Supervised Learning? A real estate company wants to sell a new house; they need to determine the price for selling the house based on its condition (e.g., size, location), as well as the sales data of their previously sold houses.
    Supervised Learning. The task is more suitable to using supervised learning because there is available training data that allows us to learn classifiers for prediction
    Clustering or Supervised Learning? Given a large number of emails, we already know whether each email is spam or not. Now we need to determine whether a newly incoming email is spam.
    Supervised Learning. The task is more suitable to using supervised learning because there is available training data that allows us to learn classifiers for prediction.
    Clustering or Supervised Learning? Find user communities in online social networks such as Facebook and Twitter.
    Clustering
    Clustering or Supervised Learning? A hospital has collected the health measurements for a number of healthy people and the patients who are infected with disease X; it needs to determine whether a new person is infected with disease X after collecting his/her health data.
    Supervised Learning. The task is more suitable to using supervised learning because there is available training data that allows us to learn classifiers for prediction.
    Clustering or Supervised Learning? Given a large number of web pages, discover the latent topics discussed by those web pages.

    Considering the k-means algorithm, after the current iteration we have three centroids (0, 1), (2, 1), and (-1, 2). Will points (0.5, 0.5) and (-0.5, 0) be assigned to the same cluster in the next iteration? 
    Yes
    Considering the k-means algorithm, after the current iteration we have three centroids (0, 1), (2, 1), and (-1, 2). Will points (2, 3) and (-0.5, 0) be assigned to the same cluster in the next iteration? 
    No
    Considering the k-means algorithm, after the current iteration we have three centroids (0, 1), (2, 1), and (-1, 2). Will points (2, 3) and (2, 0.5) be assigned to the same cluster in the next iteration?
    Yes
    True or False? The k-medoids and k-median algorithms are less sensitive to outliers than k-means.
    True. Using a median or medoid will reduce the effect of a few severe outliers, making methods like kmedoids and k-medians less sensitive to outliers
    True or False? The k-modes algorithm is designed for categorical data.
    True. This is true since k-modes is designed for categorical data.
    True or False? The centroids in the k-means algorithm may not be any observed data points
    True. Because the centroids are simply the average of all points in a cluster, this may not be a point in the cluster. For example, a cluster has points (1,2), (1,2), and (1,1), the centroid would be (1, 1.667) which is not an observed data point.
    True or False? The centroids in the k-medoids algorithm may not be any observed data points.
    False. In the k-medoids algorithm, the centroids are selected from the given data points.
    True or False? The k-means algorithm is sensitive to outliers.
    True. Outliers can have a significant impact on the mean of a cluster
    True or False? The k-means algorithm can generate non-convex clusters.
    False. k-means can only detect clusters that are linearly separable, while kernel k-means can detect some non-convex clusters.
    True or False? For different initializations, the k-means algorithm will definitely give the same clustering results.
    False. Different initializations may generate rather different clustering results (some could be far from optimal)
    True or False? The centroids in the k-means algorithm may not be any observed data points.
    True. Because the centroids are simply the average of all points in a cluster, this may not be a point in the cluster. For example, a cluster has points (1,2), (1,2), and (1,1), the centroid would be (1, 1.667) which is not an observed data point.
    True or False? The k-means algorithm can directly handle non-numerical (categorical) data.
    False. k-means requires numerical data to calculate the means.
    True or False? The k-means algorithm is sensitive to outliers.
    True. Outliers can have a significant impact on the mean of a cluster
    True or False? For different initializations, the k-means algorithm will definitely give the same clustering results
    False. Different initializations may generate rather different clustering results (some could be far from optimal).
    True or False? The centroids in the k-means algorithm may not be any observed data points.
    True. Because the centroids are simply the average of all points in a cluster, this may not be a point in the cluster. For example, a cluster has points (1,2), (1,2), and (1,1), the centroid would be (1, 1.667) which is not an observed data point.
    Is BIRCH hierarchical?
    Yes
    Is K-Means hierarchical?
    No.
    Is DBSCAN hierarchical?
    No.
    Is K-Mediod hierarchical?
    No.
    Is AGNES hierarchical?
    Yes.
    Is CHAMELEON hierarchical?
    Yes.
    True or False? CHAMELEON and CURE are better at capturing irregular shaped clusters than BIRCH
    True. By merging graphlets, CHAMELEON is able to capture complex shapes. CURE forms complex shapes by merging small disks. BIRCH tends to produce spherical clusters as limited by the diameter and radius parameters.)
    True or False? Clustering results of BIRCH are not sensitive to the insertion order of data points
    False. BIRCH is sensitive to the insertion order of data points.
    True or False? BIRCH, CURE, and CHAMELEON can only work with Euclidean distance as the similarity metric.
    False. They can work with any similarity metric
    True or False? CHAMELEON requires a graph as the input.
    False. CHAMELEON constructs the kNN graph from a set of objects by measuring the distance between objects and linking each to the k nearest neighbors
    True or False? BIRCH is better at capturing irregular shaped clusters than CHAMELEON.
    False. Quite the opposite. By merging graphlets, CHAMELEON is able to capture complex shapes. CURE forms complex shapes by merging small disks. BIRCH tends to produce spherical clusters as limited by the diameter and radius parameters.
    True or False? CHAMELEON requires a graph as the input.
    False. CHAMELEON constructs the kNN graph from a set of objects by measuring the distance between objects and linking each to the k nearest neighbors.
    True or False? Clusters in BIRCH are represented by a set of well-scattered representative points.
    False. Representative points is the mechanism used by CURE
    True or False? Each micro-cluster in BIRCH is represented by a clustering feature vector containing the number of points and the first and second moment of the points in the cluster.
    True, as per the description of the algorithm.
    True or False? BIRCH and CHAMELEON both use a two-phase algorithm where small clusters are first formed via a divisive mechanism before some other clustering algorithm is used to merge them into the final clusters
    False. The first stage of BIRCH uses a bottom-up method to build an initial in-memory CF tree. Another clustering algorithm is then applied on the micro-clusters formed in the first step to produce the final clustering. CHAMELEON, on the other hand, uses a divisive mechanism to break the kNN graph into small graphlets, which are then merged to form the final clustering.
    True or False? BIRCH, CURE, and CHAMELEON algorithms are good at detecting irregular (nonspherical) shaped clusters.
    False. While CHAMELEON and CURE are able to identify irregular shared clusters, BIRCH tends to produce spherical clusters.
    True or False? Clustering results of BIRCH are sensitive to the insertion order of data points
    True. BIRCH is sensitive to the insertion order of data points while constructing CF tree.
    True or False?In the DBSCAN algorithm, given Eps and Minpts, if a point p is density-reachable from a point q, Point q is also density-reachable from p.
    False. Incorrect when p is not a core point
    True or False? In the DBSCAN algorithm, given Eps and Minpts, if a point p is density-reachable from a point q, Point p must be directly density-reachable from q.
    False. Incorrect when the chain of points include points other than p and q
    True or False? In the DBSCAN algorithm, given Eps and Minpts, if a point p is density-reachable from a point q, Point q is density-connected to p.
    True. Correct since both p and q are density-reachable from q
    True or False? In the DBSCAN algorithm, given Eps and Minpts, if a point p is density-reachable from a point q, If there exists one point o density-reachable from p, then o is also density-reachable from q.
    True. Simply adding p into the chain will form a new chain from q to make o density-reachable.
    True or False In the DBSCAN algorithm, given Eps and Minpts, if a point p is directly density-reachable from a point q, Point q may not be directly density-reachable from p.
    True. Correct since p may not be core point
    True or False? In the DBSCAN algorithm, given Eps and Minpts, if a point p is directly density-reachable from a point q, Point p may not be density reachable from q.
    False. Incorrect since p must be density-reachable from q and the chain contains only p and q
    True or False? In the DBSCAN algorithm, given Eps and Minpts, if a point p is directly density-reachable from a point q,  Point q is density reachable from p.
    False. Incorrect since p may not be a core point
    True or False? In the DBSCAN algorithm, given Eps and Minpts, if a point p is directly density-reachable from a point q,  Point q is density-connected to p.
    True. Correct since both p and q are density-reachable from the point q
    True or False? In the DBSCAN algorithm, given Eps and Minpts, if a point p is density-connected to a point q, Point p must be density-reachable from q
    False. Incorrect. It is possible that neither p nor q is a core-point.
    True or False? In the DBSCAN algorithm, given Eps and Minpts, if a point p is density-connected to a point q, Point p may be density-reachable from q but not necessarily.
    True. As long as p is density-reachable from a certain point o, from which q is also densityreachable, they are density connected. p could be but is not necessarily density reachable from q.
    True or False? In the DBSCAN algorithm, given Eps and Minpts, if a point p is density-connected to a point q, Point q is directly density-reachable from p.
    False. Incorrect. It is possible that neither p nor q is a core-point.
    True or False? In the DBSCAN algorithm, given Eps and Minpts, if a point p is density-connected to a point q, Point q is density-connected to p.
    True. Correct since there exists a point o such that both p and q are density-reachable from o.
    True or False? In the DBSCAN algorithm, suppose eps = 4cm and Minpts = 5. Randomly select two points p, q from the observed data points. We have dist(p, q) = 1cm. Points p and q may not belong to any clusters
    True. Correct if neither p nor q is a core point
    True or False? In the DBSCAN algorithm, suppose eps = 4cm and Minpts = 5. Randomly select two points p, q from the observed data points. We have dist(p, q) = 1cm. Points p and q may be in different clusters.
    True. If (i) neither p nor q is a core point, (ii) there exists a core point o1 such that o1 is only density-reachable to p but not density reachable to q, and (iii) there exists a core point o2 such that o2 is only density-reachable to q but not density reachable to p
    True or False? In the DBSCAN algorithm, suppose eps = 4cm and Minpts = 5. Randomly select two points p, q from the observed data points. We have dist(p, q) = 1cm. Points p and q must be in different clusters.
    False. Incorrect since p and q might be noise/outliers and they do not belong to any clusters
    True or False? In the DBSCAN algorithm, suppose eps = 4cm and Minpts = 5. Randomly select two points p, q from the observed data points. We have dist(p, q) = 1cm. Points p and q must be in the same cluster
    False. Incorrect since p and q might be noise/outliers and they do not belong to any clusters
    True or False? In the DBSCAN algorithm, suppose eps = 1cm and Minpts = 1. Randomly select two points p, q from the observed data points. We have dist(p, q) = 4cm. Points p and q may be in different clusters
    True. Correct. For instance, when p and q are the only two points in the dataset, since Minpts = 1, thus p and q form two clusters.
    True or False? In the DBSCAN algorithm, suppose eps = 1cm and Minpts = 1. Randomly select two points p, q from the observed data points. We have dist(p, q) = 4cm. Points p and q must be in different clusters.
    False. Incorrect when there exists a point o such that both p and q are density-reachable from. Note that any point in the dataset for Minpts = 1 is a core point.
    True or False? In the DBSCAN algorithm, suppose eps = 1cm and Minpts = 1. Randomly select two points p, q from the observed data points. We have dist(p, q) = 4cm. Points p and q must be in the same cluster.
    False. Incorrect. For instance, there are only two points p and q in the dataset
    True or False? In the DBSCAN algorithm, suppose eps = 1cm and Minpts = 1. Randomly select two points p, q from the observed data points. We have dist(p, q) = 4cm. Points p and q may not belong to any clusters
    False. Since p and q are both core points, it is impossible for them to be outliers, which implies p and q must belong to some clusters.
    True or False? In the DBSCAN algorithm, suppose eps = 1cm and Minpts = 5. Randomly select two points p, q from the observed data points. We have dist(p, q) = 4cm. Points p and q may not be in the same cluster.
    True. Correct if there exists a core point that both p and q are density-reachable from o, then p and q are density-connected and belong to the same cluster. If there doesn’t exist such a core point, then p and q may be noise/outliers or belong to different clusters.
    True or False? In the DBSCAN algorithm, suppose eps = 1cm and Minpts = 5. Randomly select two points p, q from the observed data points. We have dist(p, q) = 4cm. Points p and q may not belong to any clusters.
    True. Correct since p and q may be noise/outliers such that they don’t belong to any cluster.
    True or False? In the DBSCAN algorithm, suppose eps = 1cm and Minpts = 5. Randomly select two points p, q from the observed data points. We have dist(p, q) = 4cm. Points p and q must be in different clusters
    False. Incorrect. p and q may be noise and do not belong to any clusters.
    True or False? In the DBSCAN algorithm, suppose eps = 1cm and Minpts = 5. Randomly select two points p, q from the observed data points. We have dist(p, q) = 4cm. Points p and q must be in the same cluster.
    False. Incorrect. p and q may be noise and do not belong to any clusters.
    CLIQUE True or False? Any point that belongs to a cluster in a 1-D subspace A may not belong to any clusters (dense regions) in any 2-D subspaces that include A.
    True. Correct since the other dimension in a 2-D subspace may belong to sparse regions, i.e., does not belong to any clusters
    CLIQUE True or False? Any point that does not belong to a cluster in a 1-D subspace A must not belong to any clusters (dense regions) in any 2-D subspaces that include A.
    True. Correct. For any data point, as long as there is one dimension that belongs to the sparse region, the data point will not belong to any dense region in a higher dimension that includes A.
    CLIQUE True or False? Any point that belongs to a cluster in a 1-D subspace A must belong to some cluster (dense region) in any 2-D subspace that includes A.
    False. Incorrect since the other dimension in a 2-D subspace may belong to sparse regions, i.e., does not belong to any clusters
    CLIQUE True or False? Any point that does not belong to a cluster in a 1-D subspace A may belong to some cluster (dense region) in any 2-D subspace that includes A.
    False. Incorrect. For any data point, as long there is one dimension that belongs to the sparse region, the data point will not belong to any dense region in a higher dimension that includes A.

    Applications of Cluster Analysis
    • An intermediate step for other tasks
    • Data summarization, or compression
    Types of hierarchical clustering algorithms
    • Agglomerative
    • Divisive
    Types of Clustering
    • Distance-based
    • Density-based
    • Grid-based
    • Probabilistic & Generative Models
    Data Matrix
    A matrix of n data points (rows) with 1 dimensions (columns)
    Dissimilarity (Distance) Matrix
    n data points of distance. Usually a symmetric triangle matrix.
    Minkowski Distance
    d(i,j) = Prt(abs(xi1-xj1)^P + abs(xi2 - xj2)^P)
    A metric
    A distance that exemplifies:
    • positivity - d(i,j) > 0 if i is not equal to j and d(i, i) = 0
    • symmetry - d(i,j) = d(j,i)
    • Triangle Inequality - d(i,j) less then or equal to d(i, k) + d(k, j)
    Manhattan Distance
    d(i,j) = abs(xi1-xj1) + abs(xi2-xj2) + ...
    Supremum Distance
    The max difference between any component of the vectors
    Symmetric Binary Variables
    Roughly the same chance of either variable being true (1).
    Asymmetric Binary Variables
    More likely for both variables to appear than neither
    Nominal Attributes
    Value represented by names
    Distance measure for nominal attributes
    m = # of matches p = total number of variables d(i,j) = (p-m)/p
    Ordinal Values
    Have order, and can be discrete or continuous.
    Cosine Similarity
    cos(d1, d2) = (d1 dot d2)/(sqrt(length of d1) * sqrt(length of d2))
    Variance
    provides a measure of how much a value of x deviates from the mean or expected value of x.
    Partitioning-Based Clustering
    Discovering groupings in the data by optimizing a specific objective function and iteratively improving the quality of the partitions.
    K-Partitioning Method
    Partitioning of a dataset D of n objects into a set of K clusters so that an object function is optimized
    Sum of Square Errors
    SSE(C) = for each cluster(for each point in that cluster(abs(xi - ck)^2)) Where ck is the centroid or mediod of the cluster.
    K Means Algorithms
    • Select k points as initial centroids
    • for k clusters by assigning each point to it's nearest centroid
    • move centroids to the mean point of each cluster
    • repeat until converged
    K Means Efficiency
    O(tKn) t = # of iterations K = # of clusters n = # of points
    True of False? K-means can discover clusters with non-convex shapes.
    False.
    True or False? K Means is sensitive to outliers and noise,
    True.
    K-Means++ Initialization
    • Select first centroid randomly
    • Select next centroid as the one that is farthest from the current one.
    • Continue until all centroids are picked.
    K-Mediods Algorithm
    • Select K points as initial representative objects
    • Assign ea point to closest mediod
    • Compute the cost of swapping mediods with random point O
    • If the cost is lower than the current mediod, switch
    • Repeat until converged
    PAM (Partitioning Around Mediods) Algorithm
    • Start with initial mediod set
    • Iteratively replace one mediod by one non-mediod if it improves total sum of SSE of the clustering
    • This is expensive.
    Is K-Mediods less sensitive to outliers than K-Means?
    Yes.
    Is K-Means less sensitive to outliers than K-medians?
    No.
    K-median Algorithm
    Just like K-Means, but use median of each feature instead.
    Can Kernel K-Means detect non-convex shapes?
    Yes.
    How does Kernel K-Means work?
    it projects the data onto high-dimensional kernel space and then performs k-means on that data. This is more computationally complex.
    Agglomerative Clustering
    Start with singleton clusters and continuously merge two clusters at a time to build a bottom-up hierarchy of clusters.
    Divisive Clustering
    Start with a huge macro-cluster and split it continuously into two groups generating a top-down hierarchy of clusters.
    AGNES
    • Use the single-link method
    • Continuously merge nodes with least dissimilarity
    • Eventually all nodes belong to some cluster
    Single Link Similarity
    Similarity between clusters is based on the similarity between their closest members. Capable of clustering non-elliptical shaped groups of objects. Sensitive to noise and outliers
    Complete Link Similarity
    Cluster similarity is based on the similarity between their farthest members. Also sensitive to outliers.
    Average Link Similarity
    Similarity between clusters is based on the average similarity between all elements in the clusters. This is expensive to compute.
    Centroid Link
    Cluster similarity is based on the distance between centroids.
    Group Averaged Agglomerative Clustering
    • N is the cardinality of the cluster
    • C is the centroid of the cluster
    • (NaCa + NbCb)/Na + Nb
    Wards Criterion
    The increase in the value of the SSE criterion for the clustering obtained by merging them into a new cluster.
    DIANA
    Divisive Clustering Algorithm. Does the inverse of AGNES. More efficient than agglomerative clustering.
    BIRCH
    A micro-cluster approach to clustering. Uses a feature (CF) tree for multi-phase clustering. Scales linearly. 
    BIRCH - Phase 1
    Scan the DB to build an initial in-memory CF-Tree.
    CF-Tree
    A multilevel compression of the data that tries to preserve the inherent clustering structure of the data.
    BIRCH - Phase 2
    Use arbitrary clustering algorithm to cluster leaf nodes of CF-Tree
    CF-Tree Stats
    N = # of data points LS = Linear sum of N points SS = Square sum of N points
    Centroid
    The middle of the cluster. The sum of all points over the total number of points.
    Radius of a Cluster
    The sqrt of the average distance from member objects to the centroid.
    Diameter of a Cluster
    The sqrt of the average mean square distance between all pairs of points in the cluster.
    CF-Tree Parameters
    • Branching Factor - Max # of children
    • Max DIameter of sub-clusters stored at leaf node
    BIRCH Concerns
    • Sensitive to insertion order of data points
    • Due to the fixed size of leaf nodes, clusters may not be natural
    • Clusters tend to be spherical given the radius and diameter measures
    CURE
    Clustering using well-scattered points. Incorporates features of both single and average link. Captures clusters of arbitrary shapes. More robust for outliers.
    CHAMELEON
    An agglomerative, graph-base Clustering. Clusters are merged only if the interconnectivity and closeness between clusters are high relative to the internal connectivity of the clusters and closeness of items within the clusters.
    k-NN Graph
    Points p and q are connected if q is among the top-k closest neighbors of p.
    Absolute Interconnectivity
    The sum of the weight of the edges that connect vertices between clusters.
    Internal Interconnectivity
    The weighted sum of edges that partition the graph into two roughly equal parts.
    Relative Closeness
    The absolute closeness between clusters normalized with respect to the internal closeness of those clusters.
    Hierarchical Clustering Problems
    • Nontrivial to choose good distance measure
    • Hard to handle missing attribute values
    • Optimization goal is not clear
    Generative Clustering Model
    Regard the set of data objects to be clustered as a sample of the underlying data generation mechanism to be analyzed.
    DBSCAN
    A density-based clustering algorithm. Can be used to discover arbitrary cluster shapes. It is sensitive to the setting of parameters.
    DBSCAN - Eps
    Maximum radius of a neighborhood
    DBSCAN - MinPts
    The minimum number of points in the Eps-neighborhood of a point.
    DBSCAN - Outlier
    Not in any cluster
    DBSCAN - Core Point
    A point in a dense neighborhood
    DBSCAN - Border Point
    In a cluster, but neighborhood is not dense
    DBSCAN - Directly Density-Reachable
    Point p is directly density-reachable from point q if p belongs to q's neighborhood and q's neighborhood is greater than or equal to MinPts
    DBSCAN - Density-Reachable
    If there is a chain of points such that each point is directly density-reachable from the point before it.
    DBSCAN - Density-Connected
    If there is a point o such that both p and q are density reachable from o
    DBSCAN Algorithm
    • Arbitrarily set a point p
    • Retrieve all points density-reachable from p
    • If p is a core point form a cluster, else move to next point in the db.
    • Continue until all points are processed
    OPTICS
    High-density points should be processed first. Stores clustering order using core distance, and reachability distance. Clusters coorespond to valleys
    STING
    A grid-based clustering algorithm. Cells are formed at different levels of resolution form a tree-like structure. Parameters of higher-level cells can be calculated using lower-level cells.
    STING Advantages
    • Query-independent
    • Easy to Parallelize
    • Incremental Updates
    • Very Efficient
    STING Disadvantage
    It's probabilistic nature may imply a loss of accuracy in query processing.
    CLIQUE
    Density and grid-based subspace clustering algorithm. Estimates density by counting number of points in a grid cell. Uses apriori principle when clustering.
    CLIQUE Strengths
    • Automatically find subspaces of highest dimensionality if clusters exist
    • Insensitive to the order of records
    • Scales linearly with the size of the input
    CLIQUE Weakness
    • The quality of the results crucially depends on the appropriate choice of # and width of grid cells.
    Categories of Cluster Evaluation Measures
    • Internal
    • External
    • Relative
    Internal Evaluation Measure
    • Unsupervised
    • Derived from data
    • Considers how well the clusters separated and how compact they are
    External Evaluation Method
    • Supervised
    • Employ criteria outside the data set
    • Compare a clustering against prior or expert knowledge
    Relative Evaluation Measure
    • Directly compare different clusterings obtained via different parameter settings
    Constraint-Based Clustering Criteria
    • Cluster Homogeneity
    • Cluster Completeness
    • Rag Bag better than Alien
    • Small Cluster Preservation
    Cluster Homogeneity
    The purer the cluster, the better
    Cluster Completeness
    Assign Objects belonging to the same category in the ground truth to the same cluster
    Rag Bag better than Alien
    Putting heterogeneous objects into a pure cluster is penalized more than putting it in a "rag bag"
    Small Cluster Preservation
    Splitting a small category into pieces is more harmful than splitting a large category into pieces
    Purity
    External Measure. Quantifies the extent that a cluster contains points only from one partition. Perfect if purity = 1.
    Maximum Matching
    External Measure. Only one cluster can match one ground truth partition. 
    Precision
    Same as purity
    Recall
    Points in cluster over total points in that ground truth partition.
    F-Measure
    External Measure. Harmonic mean of precision and recall.
    Normalized Mutual Information
    External Measure. Quantifies the amount of shared info between the clustering and partitioning. Range 0 to 1. 1 is best clustering.
    Pairwise True Positive
    If two points are in the same cluster and belong to the same partitioning.
    Pairwise False Positive
    If two points are in different clusters but belong to the same partitioning.
    Pairwise False Negative
    If two points belong to the same cluster, but belong to different partitions.
    Pairwise True Negative
    If two points belong to different clusters and different partitions.
    Jaccard Coefficient
    External Measure. Fraction of TP points, after ignoring the TN. Asymmetric.
    Rand Statistic
    External Measure. TP and TN points over total number of points. Symmetric. 1 is a perfect clustering.
    Fowlkes-Mallow Measure
    External Measure. Geometric mean of precision and recall.
    Beta-CV Measure
    Internal Measure. The ratio of the mean intra-cluster distance to the mean inter-cluster distance. The smaller the better.
    Normalized Cut
    Internal Measure. The higher the value the better the clustering.
    Modularity
    Internal Measure. Graph Clustering. Measures the differences between observed and expected fraction of weights on edges within the clusters. The smaller the value the better the clustering.
    Silhouette Coefficient
    Internal and Relative Measure. Checks cluster cohesion and separation. 
    Cluster Stability
    Clusterings obtained from several datasets sampled from the same underlying distribution shall be similar or "stable".
    Elbow Method
    Use the turning point in the curve of the sum of within-cluster variance to select the number of clusters.
    Cross Validation
    Divide a data set into m parts. Use m-1 parts to obtain clustering model. Use remaining part to test quality of model.
    Clusterability Assessment Models
    • Spatial Histogram
    • Distance Distribution
    • Hopkins Statistic
    Spatial Histogram
    Contrast the histogram of input with histogram generated from random data
    Distance Distribution
    Compare pairwise point distance from the data with those from the randomly generated samples.
    Hopkins Statistic
    A sparse sampling test for spatial randomness
